      "content": "Proponents of a genetic component to IQ differences often point to the fact that IQ scores are heritable, with estimates suggesting that 40-80% of individual differences in IQ can be attributed to genetic factors. They also argue that the distribution of IQ scores within racial groups is more similar to a normal distribution, suggesting a genetic basis, whereas the distribution of IQ scores between racial groups is more skewed, suggesting a genetic difference. Additionally, they often cite the work of Richard Lynn and Tatu Vanhanen, who have published studies suggesting that certain racial groups, such as East Asians, have higher average IQs due to genetic factors. They also argue that the \"IQ gap\" between racial groups cannot be explained by differences in education, nutrition, or other environmental factors.",
